Streams, Global Tables, T-T-L, and P-I-T-R.

DynamoDB Streams is a twenty-four-hour change log of item-level modifications. Every create, update, and delete on a table can be captured as a stream record, ordered per partition key. You choose what each record contains: keys only, the new image, the old image, or both. Lambda consumes streams via an event source mapping, with delivery scaled automatically to the number of shards, and this powers a lot of DynamoDB patterns: event-driven downstream work, like fanning a write out to email or push notifications; search indexing, by replicating writes to OpenSearch for full-text search; audit logging, by appending every change to S3 via Firehose; materialised views, maintaining a derived projection in another DynamoDB table; and replication, which is the basis of Global Tables.

Global Tables is DynamoDB's multi-region, multi-active replication. Every region accepts both reads and writes, changes replicate in about a second, and conflicts resolve last-writer-wins. It's for globally distributed applications and multi-region disaster recovery.

Two operational features round it out. T-T-L, time-to-live, auto-deletes items after a per-item expiry timestamp, an attribute holding a Unix epoch in seconds, removing them in the background, typically within forty-eight hours. T-T-L deletes don't consume write-capacity-units, and they show up in Streams, so cleanup logic can hang off them; the caveat is that items can still appear in reads until the background sweep runs, so filter on the expiry attribute if strict expiry matters. And P-I-T-R, point-in-time recovery, is continuous backup: with it enabled, you can restore the table to any second within the last thirty-five days, recovering a new table at that timestamp. It's the standard guard against application bugs or a delete-without-where accident; on-demand backups are the manual snapshot companion.
